sentence_chunk: Data and Artificial Intelligence  The Data and Artificial Intelligence category includes five main career paths: Business Intelligence, Data Engineering, Machine Learning (ML) Engineering, Data Science/AI Science, and AI Applied Research. Entry-level roles typically include Data Analyst or Associate Data Engineer, which serve as starting points focusing on data analysis, report generation, and basic data manipulation. The Associate Data Engineer role also provides exposure to data engineering tasks, creating a pathway into that specialization. As professionals gain experience, they can specialize in roles such as Data Engineer, responsible for building and maintaining data infrastructure, including databases, ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) processes, and data pipelines. AI/ML Engineers focus on developing and deploying AI and Machine Learning models, requiring expertise in algorithms, programming, and machine learning techniques.

Data Scientists or AI Scientists engage in research, development, and evaluation of AI/ML models, leveraging statistical modeling and machine learning skills. Business Intelligence Managers, on the other hand, oversee BI teams, developing dashboards, reports, and insights that inform business decisions. Data Architects play a crucial role in designing and overseeing an organization's data infrastructure, ensuring data accessibility, reliability, and security for both BI and AI applications. At the senior level, professionals may advance to roles such as Senior Data Engineer or Senior AI/ML Engineer, which require deep technical expertise and often involve team leadership and mentoring. Business Intelligence Directors oversee the BI function, setting strategies and ensuring alignment with business goals.
The Head of Data Science and AI leads the overall data science and AI strategy, managing teams of data scientists, AI/ML engineers, and researchers to

ensure AI initiatives deliver business value. The highest executive roles include Chief Data Officer or Chief AI Officer, responsible for defining the overall vision, strategy, and roadmap for data and AI within an organization, driving data-driven decision-making and innovation. Career progression typically follows a natural trajectory, where entry-level roles such as Data Analyst or Associate Data Engineer lead to specialization in Data Engineering, AI/ML Engineering, or Business Intelligence Management. Data Engineers and AI/ML Engineers work closely together, as strong data infrastructure is essential for successful AI/ML implementations. Data Scientists frequently collaborate with AI/ML Engineers to deploy models into production, while Data Architects ensure a unified and efficient data ecosystem that supports both BI and AI initiatives.

Leadership positions such as BI Director or Head of Data Science and AI require a combination of technical expertise, business acumen, and leadership skills. It is important to note that career paths in Data and AI are flexible and can vary based on individual skills, interests, and organizational needs. Given the rapidly evolving nature of the field, continuous learning and adaptation are crucial for long-term success. tasks, providing a pathway into that specialization. This role often acts as a feeder into more specialized data roles.  With experience, individuals can specialize as Data Engineers, building and maintaining data infrastructure. This involves working with databases, ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) processes, and data pipelines. A strong data engineering background is essential for supporting both BI and AI initiatives.

Alternatively, they can become AI/ML Engineers, developing and deploying AI/Machine Learning models. It requires a strong understanding of algorithms, programming, and machine learning techniques. AI/ML Engineers work closely with Data Scientists to put models into production.  Data Scientist/AI Scientist roles involve researching, developing, and evaluating AI/ML models. They require a deep understanding of statistical modeling, machine learning, and domain expertise.

Data Scientists often work on more exploratory and research-oriented projects. Business Intelligence Managers oversee BI teams and Data Architects design data infrastructure. They ensure that data is accessible, reliable, and secure for both BI and AI purposes.  Senior roles include Senior Data Engineer/Senior AI/ML Engineer, Business Intelligence Director, Head of Data Science and AI, and Chief Data Officer/Chief AI Officer. These roles often require a combination of technical expertise, business acumen, and leadership skills.

Career progression can involve moving from Data Analyst/Associate Data Engineer to Data Engineering or AI/ML Engineering, or even into Business Intelligence Management. Data Engineers and AI/ML Engineers collaborate closely, as do Data Scientists and AI/ML Engineers. Specific career paths may vary based on individual skills, interests, and organizational needs, and continuous learning is essential in the evolving Data and AI field.  Data Analyst/Associate Data Engineer Job Description: The Data Analyst/Associate Data Engineer analyzes historical data from various sources (industry reports, public information, field reports, etc.)

to support business and product decisions. This role involves data cleaning, transformation, and using development tools to generate reports, dashboards, and analytical solutions. The Data Analyst/Associate Data Engineer collaborates with internal teams on projects, contributing to data collection, processing, and warehousing tasks. This may include collecting, parsing, analyzing, and visualizing large datasets. A successful Data Analyst/Associate Data Engineer is meticulous, detail-oriented, and enjoys working with data.

They possess strong analytical and communication skills and are eager to learn. Critical Skills: The Data Analyst/Associate Data Engineer needs to have proficiency in leadership, developing people, computational thinking, communication, and creative thinking.

Technical Skills & Competencies: They should also have technical skills and competencies such as budgeting, business innovation, business needs analysis, business performance management, data analytics, data engineering, data ethics, data visualization, database administration, design thinking practice, networking, project management, and stakeholder management. Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include identifying and translating business needs into analytics and reporting requirements, recommending data types and sources, and assisting in identifying potential business intelligence service offerings. They also gather, clean, and validate data, perform basic ETL processes, analyze data to identify trends and patterns, propose solutions, and develop automated and logical data models. Additionally, they translate analyses into clear business language, design data reports and visualizations, and adhere to the Model AI Governance Framework and the Personal Data Protection Act 2012 in all their performance expectations. Business Intelligence Manager Job Description: The Business Intelligence Manager identifies and translates market opportunities into actionable recommendations for the organization.

They supervise professionals in gathering and analyzing business intelligence (BI) data to support informed business decisions. The BI Manager ensures timely reporting of data analysis outcomes and effectively communicates findings, insights, and recommendations to business leaders. This role involves developing data and information quality metrics, researching new technologies, and developing business cases for enterprise-wide BI solutions. The BI Manager also develops guidelines for data insight reporting and manages BI-related projects from end to end. A successful BI Manager has a deep passion for

analyzing and resolving complex problems through a systematic approach. They possess intellectual curiosity and engage effectively with stakeholders to understand business issues. Critical Skills: The Business Intelligence Manager should possess skills in communication, problem-solving, sense-making, transdisciplinary thinking, and creative thinking. Technical Skills & Competencies: They also need technical skills and competencies, including budgeting, business innovation, business needs analysis, business performance management, data analytics, data ethics, data governance, data visualization, design thinking practice, learning and development, manpower planning, networking, people and performance management, project management, stakeholder management, and strategy implementation. Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions involve evaluating business plans, recommending data types for performance measurement, overseeing design proposals, influencing data integration, and creating new BI service offerings.

They also manage data analysis, oversee data processes, define data quality metrics, synthesize trends, and set guidelines for reporting. Additionally, they manage budgets, monitor team achievements, propose operational plans, optimize resources, develop learning roadmaps, and manage performance and development processes. Business Intelligence Director Job Description: The Business Intelligence Director sets the strategy, vision, and policy for managing the day-to-day strategic and tactical operations of the

business intelligence (BI) teams. This role encompasses responsibilities related to historical data sourcing and preparation, data storage, reporting, analytics, data exploration, and information delivery. The BI Director works with senior management to understand and prioritize data and information requirements and is responsible for setting up the BI strategy within the organization. They oversee the development of testing methodology and criteria, standards, policies, and procedures for BI tools and systems, as well as budgeting and planning. A successful BI Director possesses strong analytical thinking skills and the ability to adopt a broader perspective for BI solutions.

They can effectively influence key stakeholders and promote a data-driven approach to resolve business issues. Critical Skills: The Business Intelligence Director needs to have proficiency in problem-solving, communication, leadership, lifelong learning, and interpersonal skills. Technical Skills & Competencies: Additionally, they should possess technical skills and competencies in budgeting, business agility, business continuity, business risk management, change management, data ethics, data governance, data strategy, enterprise architecture, emerging technology synthesis, IT governance, IT standards, organizational analysis, performance management, quality standards, research, sustainability management, stakeholder management, and strategy planning. Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include outlining the BI vision, overseeing BI architecture, establishing an approach for identifying business needs, providing rationale for BI investments, and providing thought leadership on BI solutions. They also define the analysis process, advise on data collection, set guidelines for data structuring, present insights and

recommendations, develop BI standards, create data governance initiatives, manage resources, oversee learning roadmaps, and implement succession planning. Data Engineer Job Description: The Data Engineer supports the design, implementation, and maintenance of data flow channels and data processing systems that support the collection, storage, batch and real-time processing, and analysis of information in a scalable, repeatable, and secure manner. They focus on defining optimal solutions for data collection, processing, and warehousing, designing, coding, and testing data systems, and implementing them into the internal infrastructure. The Data Engineer works on collecting, parsing, managing, analyzing, and visualizing large sets of data to turn information into insights accessible through multiple platforms. A successful Data Engineer is passionate about numbers and working with large datasets.

They have a keenness for understanding business processes and resolving challenges to provide solutions with the help of clean and interlinked databases and architectures. Critical Skills: The Data Engineer should have proficiency in leadership, developing people, communication, transdisciplinary thinking, and computational thinking. Technical Skills & Competencies: They also need technical skills and competencies in business needs analysis, change management, computational modelling, configuration tracking, data design, data engineering, data ethics, data governance, data migration, data strategy, database administration, emerging technology synthesis, learning and development, manpower planning, people and performance management, project management, quality standards, security

architecture, stakeholder management, strategy implementation, and system integration. Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include identifying suitable data structures, determining technical system requirements, and staying abreast of the latest technologies. They also build and maintain data pipelines, develop code for data processing, test pipelines for scalability, consolidate data storage solutions, develop prototypes, monitor performance, develop backup systems, and implement security measures. Additionally, they assist in integrating data systems, develop tools to improve data flows, automate data processes, and test configurations for efficiency. Senior Data Engineer Job Description: The Senior Data Engineer designs, implements, and oversees the maintenance of data flow channels and data processing systems that support the collection, storage, batch and real-time processing, and analysis of information from structured and unstructured sources in a scalable, repeatable, and secure manner.

They assist data scientists with extracting valuable insights from datasets to derive actionable recommendations that support business requirements. The Senior Data Engineer is involved in rollouts, upgrades, implementation, and release of data system changes as required for streamlining internal practices. A successful Senior Data Engineer possesses a natural inclination for understanding business processes and relevant data requirements. They easily build rapport with others and can effectively communicate ideas and recommendations to influence stakeholders and decisions.

Critical Skills: The Senior Data Engineer needs to have proficiency in leadership, communication, developing people, transdisciplinary thinking, and computational thinking. Technical Skills & Competencies: They should also have technical skills and competencies in business needs analysis, change management, computational modelling, configuration tracking, data design, data engineering, data ethics, data governance, data strategy, database administration, emerging technology synthesis, learning and development, manpower planning, people and performance management, project management, quality standards, security architecture, stakeholder management, strategy planning, and system integration. Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include assessing data structures, translating business needs into technical requirements, and evaluating technologies for integration and storage. They also build and maintain data pipelines, validate data processes, create data storage plans, lead project rollouts, analyze data system performance, build metadata systems, formulate backup plans, and ensure data security. Additionally, they evaluate existing technologies, resolve data integrity issues, identify opportunities for improvement, and automate processes.

Data Architect Job Description: The Data Architect designs systems to facilitate access to and retrieval of information. They plan, design, develop, and test internal information-delivery solutions and data models with a focus on providing a positive user experience. They work with end users to specify requirements, create, and implement designs to meet internal and client-facing objectives. Data

Architects develop information management standards and practices in compliance with data privacy policies, ethics, and governance frameworks. A successful Data Architect integrates diverse needs and perspectives from internal and external clients and possesses a creative mind to develop new and fresh ideas and solutions. They possess strong leadership and communication abilities and can influence key stakeholders and clients. Critical Skills: The Data Architect should possess skills in problem-solving, communication, interpersonal skills, leadership, and service orientation. Technical Skills & Competencies: They also need technical skills and competencies in budgeting, business agility, business continuity, business risk management, change management, data ethics, data governance, data strategy, enterprise architecture, emerging technology synthesis, IT governance, IT standards, organizational analysis, performance management, quality standards, research, sustainability management, and stakeholder management.

Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include determining data engineering requirements, advising on data requirements, establishing data ethics guidelines, and advising on machine learning technologies. They also define information flow, assess existing systems, guide alignment with enterprise architecture, develop data migration strategies, and communicate design recommendations. Additionally, they formulate strategies for model production, formulate AI/ML development pipeline strategies, provide technical guidance for scaling, create deployment blueprints, ensure ethical deployment, and manage resources. Chief Data Officer/Chief AI Officer

Job Description: The Chief Data Officer/Chief AI Officer leads the organization's data and artificial intelligence (AI) strategy, ensuring alignment with business goals and ethical considerations. They promote a data-driven culture, identify opportunities to leverage data and AI for innovation and value creation, and oversee the development and implementation of data governance frameworks, policies, and standards. The Chief Data Officer/Chief AI Officer also champions the ethical and responsible use of AI, fosters collaboration between business units and technical teams, and stays abreast of emerging trends and technologies in the data and AI landscape. A successful Chief Data Officer/Chief AI Officer possesses strong leadership, communication, and strategic thinking skills, coupled with a deep understanding of data management, AI technologies, and ethical considerations. Critical Skills: The Chief Data Officer/Chief AI Officer should have proficiency in problem-solving, communication, interpersonal skills, leadership, and service orientation.

Technical Skills & Competencies: They also need technical skills and competencies in budgeting, business agility, business continuity, business risk management, change management, data ethics, data governance, data strategy, enterprise architecture, emerging technology synthesis, IT governance, IT standards, organizational analysis, performance management, quality standards, research, sustainability management, stakeholder management, and strategy planning. Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include establishing data and AI strategy, aligning data and AI priorities, formulating approaches to maximize data value, developing strategies for technology integration, promoting

industry best practices, and driving a culture of data privacy compliance. They also design data-driven initiatives, identify high-value opportunities, advise on new tools and techniques, determine the potential impact of analytics, oversee the implementation of data initiatives, formulate project prioritization strategies, establish performance measures, review emerging trends, analyze technology landscapes, identify potential IP opportunities, oversee IP management systems, act as a subject matter expert for IP infringements, build strategic relationships, develop stakeholder management plans, lead engagement initiatives, source data analytics opportunities, ensure data compliance, develop strategies to build data and AI capabilities, drive talent management initiatives, ensure ethical AI solutions, and lead succession planning. Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning Engineer Job Description: The Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning Engineer1 develops, implements, and maintains AI/ML models and algorithms to address business challenges and drive innovation. They work with large datasets, apply machine learning techniques, and leverage cloud platforms to build and deploy AI solutions. The AI/ML Engineer collaborates with data scientists, data engineers, and software developers to integrate AI/ML models into applications and systems.

They also stay updated on the latest advancements in AI/ML technologies and contribute to the development of best practices and standards within the organization. A successful AI/ML Engineer possesses strong programming skills, a deep understanding of machine learning algorithms, and the ability to translate business requirements into AI solutions.

Critical Skills: The Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning Engineer should have proficiency in leadership, developing people, transdisciplinary thinking, computational thinking, and communication. Senior Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning Engineer Job Description: The Senior Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning Engineer2 leads the development and implementation of complex AI/ML models and algorithms, providing technical guidance and mentorship to junior engineers. They conduct research, evaluate new technologies, and contribute to the strategic direction of AI/ML initiatives within the organization.
The Senior AI/ML Engineer also collaborates with stakeholders to identify business opportunities

and translate them into AI solutions. They ensure the quality, scalability, and ethical considerations of AI/ML models and contribute to the development of intellectual property. A successful Senior AI/ML Engineer possesses strong leadership, communication, and problem-solving skills, along with expertise in AI/ML technologies and a deep understanding of ethical implications. Technical Skills & Competencies: They should also have technical skills and competencies in business needs analysis, change management, cloud computing, computational modelling, computer vision technology, configuration tracking, data design, data engineering, data governance, data strategy, database administration, emerging technology synthesis, intelligent reasoning, pattern recognition systems, problem management, project management, security architecture, self-learning systems, stakeholder management, system integration, test planning, and text analytics and processing.

Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include researching and recommending machine learning algorithms, guiding the selection of datasets, overseeing model evaluation, advising on algorithm suitability, leading the development of new models, developing safety measures, analyzing potential biases, designing experiments, leading analysis and testing, synthesizing insights, leading prototype development, providing guidance on model development, enhancing transparency, performing preliminary patentability analysis, assisting in IP creation and management, and assisting in IP due diligence.

Head of Data Science and Artificial Intelligence Job Description: The Head of Data Science and Artificial Intelligence leads the data science and AI teams, setting the strategic direction for research, development, and implementation of AI solutions. They foster a culture of innovation, collaboration, and ethical AI practices within the organization. The Head of Data Science and AI also oversees the development of AI models, algorithms, and applications, ensuring alignment with business objectives and ethical guidelines. They stay abreast of emerging trends and technologies in the field and contribute to the organization's intellectual property portfolio. A successful Head of Data Science and AI possesses strong leadership, communication, and technical skills, coupled with a deep understanding of AI technologies, data management, and ethical considerations.

Critical Skills: The Head of Data Science and Artificial Intelligence needs to have proficiency in problem-solving, communication, leadership, interpersonal skills, and transdisciplinary thinking. implementation of new technologies, overseeing AI research and development, communicating and ensuring compliance with data privacy policies, directing engagement initiatives, reviewing research outcomes, establishing policies for model tuning, developing feasibility analysis plans, synthesizing insights from research, approving AI solutions, communicating insights for decision-making, building partnerships, identifying potential IP commercialization opportunities, liaising with external vendors, ensuring compliance with IP legislation, presenting data and AI model development outcomes, creating resources for data and AI adoption, articulating business value, managing resources, overseeing learning roadmaps, and implementing succession planning. Data Scientist/Artificial Intelligence Scientist Job Description: The Data Scientist/Artificial Intelligence Scientist analyzes large and complex datasets to extract meaningful insights and develop predictive models. They apply statistical methods, machine learning techniques, and AI algorithms to solve business problems and drive innovation. The Data Scientist/AI Scientist also communicates findings to stakeholders, collaborates with other teams to implement AI solutions, and stays updated on the latest advancements in the field. A successful Data Scientist/AI Scientist possesses strong analytical and problem-solving skills, a deep understanding of statistical modeling and machine learning, and the ability to communicate complex technical concepts to a non-technical audience.
Critical Skills: The Data Scientist/Artificial Intelligence Scientist needs to have proficiency in leadership, developing people, communication, computational thinking, and lifelong learning.

Technical Skills & Competencies: They should also have technical skills and competencies in business innovation, business needs analysis, computer vision technology, data design, data ethics, data governance, data strategy, design thinking practice, emerging technology synthesis, intelligent reasoning, organizational design, pattern recognition systems, project management, quality standards, research, self-learning systems, stakeholder management, and text analytics and processing. Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include defining objectives and hypotheses for research, analyzing potential biases in datasets, conducting data extraction and integration, developing models and algorithms, performing model comparison, selecting the best model based on evaluation criteria, accounting for data ethics, interpreting and evaluating model performance, conducting testing on the final model, scaling and deploying models, initiating autonomous monitoring, documenting modeling techniques, enabling end-user capability, creating reports and deliverables, developing presentations, and contributing to the creation of leading-edge resources. Artificial Intelligence Applied Researcher Job Description: The Artificial Intelligence Applied Researcher conducts research and development in the field of AI, focusing on the application of AI technologies to real-world problems. They explore new AI algorithms, models, and approaches, conduct experiments, and analyze results to advance the state-of-the-art in AI. The AI Applied Researcher also collaborates with other researchers, engineers, and stakeholders to translate research findings into practical AI solutions.
They contribute to the development of intellectual property and stay abreast of the latest advancements in AI research. A successful AI Applied Researcher

possesses strong research skills, a deep understanding of AI algorithms and technologies, and the ability to bridge the gap between theoretical research and practical applications. Critical Skills: The Artificial Intelligence Applied Researcher needs to have proficiency in leadership, developing people, communication, computational thinking, and lifelong learning. Technical Skills & Competencies: They should also have technical skills and competencies in business innovation, business needs analysis, computer vision technology, data design, data ethics, data governance, data strategy, design thinking practice, emerging technology synthesis, intelligent reasoning, organizational design, pattern recognition systems, project management, quality standards, research, self-learning systems, stakeholder management, and text analytics and processing. Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include planning and designing AI research projects, managing project plans and timelines, evaluating research methodology, connecting with academics, reviewing AI literature, synthesizing research, documenting and presenting research outcomes, ensuring data quality, assessing data extraction methods, exploring new data sources, analyzing potential biases, designing experiments, leading analysis and simulations, synthesizing insights, leading prototype development, providing guidance on model development, enhancing transparency, performing preliminary patentability analysis, assisting in IP creation and management, and assisting in IP due diligence. Software and Applications

Within the dynamic realm of Information and Communications Technology (ICT), the software and applications division offers a structured yet evolving career landscape, particularly for those specializing in software engineering. A common progression begins with foundational roles such as Associate Software Engineer, Associate Embedded Systems Engineer, and Associate UI Designer. These entry-level positions provide crucial hands-on experience in their respective domains, laying the groundwork for future specialization. Individuals in these roles typically engage in core programming skill development, grasp fundamental software development principles, and contribute to projects under the guidance of senior team members. As professionals gain experience, they progress to mid-level positions, often becoming Software Engineers, Embedded Systems Engineers, or UI Designers.

These roles demand greater autonomy and responsibility, requiring individuals to manage more complex tasks and contribute significantly to project success. Software Engineers focus on the development and maintenance of software applications, while Embedded Systems Engineers specialize in crafting software for hardware devices. UI Designers, on the other hand, are concerned with creating intuitive and aesthetically pleasing user interfaces. The mid-level also sees the emergence of the DevOps Engineer, a critical role that bridges development and operations. DevOps Engineers streamline the software development lifecycle through automation and process optimization, employing techniques like continuous integration and continuous delivery.

For those inclined towards leadership, the Software Engineering Manager position offers an entry point into team management, encompassing project planning, task delegation, performance evaluation, and mentorship.

At the senior level, technical expertise and strategic thinking become paramount. Software Architects design the high-level structure of software systems, making key decisions about technology selection, system architecture, and system integration. Lead UI Designers guide teams of UI designers, establishing the overall design direction for products and ensuring a cohesive and user-centric experience. Embedded Systems Engineering Managers, mirroring the responsibilities of Software Engineering Managers, lead teams of embedded systems engineers. The Head of Software Engineering oversees multiple software engineering teams, focusing on strategic planning, resource allocation, and the delivery of high-quality software products.

The executive tier comprises leadership roles that shape the organization's technological direction. The Chief Technology Officer (CTO) is responsible for the overall technology strategy, driving innovation and ensuring alignment with business objectives. The Chief Information Officer (CIO) focuses on the organization's IT infrastructure and systems, ensuring security, reliability, and operational support. These executive leaders make critical decisions regarding technology investments and the implementation of systems that enable organizational success. While this progression represents a common pathway, it is important to acknowledge the interconnectedness of these roles.

Collaboration is essential, with Software Engineers often working closely with UI Designers and DevOps Engineers. Furthermore, individual career trajectories are not always linear. Professionals may choose to specialize in particular areas or transition between different roles throughout their careers. Although not explicitly depicted, related functions such as Quality Assurance and Project Management are integral to the

software development process and often exist as parallel or complementary career paths. Associate Software Engineer Job Description: The Associate Software Engineer applies subject matter knowledge in applications development, possessing well-developed skills in designing, developing, testing, debugging, and implementing software applications or specialized utility programs to support end-users' needs on platforms. They support regular updates and recommend improvements to existing applications. They work under limited supervision to effectively deal with unfamiliar issues and follow recommended coding standards and secure-coding principles to avoid security vulnerabilities. They provide technical support to the quality testing teams and work in a team setting, proficient in the programming languages required by the organization.

They are familiar with software development tools and standards and the relevant software platforms on which the solution is deployed. The Associate Software Engineer is a keen learner and can apply structured, analytical thinking to develop applications. They are a strong team player who communicates ideas and gets along with others easily.  Critical Skills: The Associate Software Engineer needs to have proficiency in computational thinking, problem-solving, lifelong learning, communication, and teamwork. Technical Skills & Competencies: They should also have technical skills and competencies in Agile Software Development, applications development, applications integration, applications support and enhancement, business environment analysis, business needs analysis, configuration tracking, data design, emerging technology synthesis, problem management, project

management, software configuration, software design, software testing, stakeholder management, system integration, test planning, and user interface design. Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include analyzing user and business requirements, managing the design of software, managing software construction processes, overseeing software testing, overseeing security provisions in software, and managing software management configuration (SCM). This includes tasks like participating in discussions with stakeholders to understand user requirements, conducting requirements analysis, preparing documentation, assisting in writing proposals, and proposing new technologies. They also assist in design tasks, apply design patterns, participate in reviews, carry out static analysis, and assist in developing simulations and prototypes. Their work involves integration testing, collecting code quality measures, generating codes and systems, creating unit tests, and achieving test coverage goals.

They identify testing criteria, adhere to test plans, assist with test case development, implement test environments, and collect and analyze results. They follow secure-coding principles, adhere to security assessment metrics, and perform code reviews to identify vulnerabilities. They assist in determining SCM constraints, provide measurement data, and help identify software configuration items. Software Engineer Job Description: The Software Engineer leads important projects and possesses the capability to make breakthroughs in designing, developing, testing, debugging, and implementing software applications or specialized utility programs supporting end users' needs on platforms. They plan and coordinate

regular updates and recommend improvements to existing applications. They identify and resolve issues with organization-wide and long-term impacts. They identify security risks, create requirements to capture security issues, and perform initial threat modeling to ensure coding standards meet security requirements. They develop and maintain the software configuration management plan and oversee building, verification, and implementing software releases. They work in a team setting and are proficient in programming languages required by the organization. They are familiar with software development tools and standards and the relevant software platforms on which the solution is deployed. The Software Engineer is imaginative and creative in exploring a range of application designs and solutions. They engage with and support others in the team, readily putting forth their ideas clearly and compellingly.  Critical Skills: The Software Engineer needs to have proficiency in computational thinking, problem-solving, lifelong learning, communication, and teamwork.

Technical Skills & Competencies: They should also have technical skills and competencies in applications development, applications integration, applications support and enhancement, budgeting, business environment analysis, business needs analysis, business negotiation, business requirements mapping, business risk management, change management, configuration tracking, data design, database administration, emerging technology synthesis, performance management, problem management, product management, project management, quality standards, software configuration, software design, software testing, solution architecture, stakeholder management, system integration, test planning, and user interface design.

Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include analyzing user and business requirements, managing software design, managing software construction processes, overseeing software testing, overseeing security provisions in software, and managing software management configuration (SCM). They validate user requirements and design specifications, translate user requirements into technical specifications, formulate software requirement specifications, recommend approaches that balance security, stability, and performance needs, and provide technical guidance on proposed solutions and alternatives. They design software components and modules, determine design alternatives and perform trade-off analysis, create multiple views of the software system and design high-level organization of a software system, facilitate software design reviews, lead static analysis tasks to evaluate design quality, develop and use simulation and prototypes to evaluate software design quality. They assist in selecting processes, models, languages, and tools for software construction, perform code re-factoring, review detailed designs and code to ensure quality requirements are met, establish project standards for designs and codes, and lead code reviews and inspections. They identify stakeholders participating in testing activities, design software test plans and criteria for regression testing, design the test environment and test case scenarios, specify test cases for the selected testing technique, and analyze defect arrival rate and failure intensity data.

They identify security risks and create requirements to capture security issues, perform initial threat modeling, model threats and associated risks of new and modified systems, identify the attack surface of new and modified systems, establish project coding standards to avoid security vulnerabilities, review and approve coding standards to avoid security vulnerabilities. They develop and maintain the SCM plan, assist in specifying the SCM measures to be used, procure SCM tools, develop and tailor tools for

generating SCM audit reports, maintain mechanisms for recording and reporting SCM information, oversee the building, verification and implementation of software releases, and ensure the execution and documentation of approved changes. Software Architect Job Description: The Software Architect analyzes, designs, and develops roadmaps and implementation plans based on a current versus future state business architecture and reviews recommendations to software architectural standards for approval. They lead and facilitate the software architecture governance process based on the enterprise architecture governance structure and manage exceptions to architectural standards at a software level. They assess near-term needs to establish business priorities and align architectural requirements with IT strategy. They consult with clients and IT teams on software architecture solutions and provide recommendations on emerging technology to senior management.

They oversee developing guidelines and standards to be used in software development and integration and formulate the conceptual and detailed architecture for developing applications. The Software Architect is imaginative and creative, drawing connections from diverse disciplines to develop application architectures and solutions. They enjoy the challenge of analyzing and resolving complex issues and can interact effectively with others to gain buy-in where required. Critical Skills: The Software Architect needs to have proficiency in communication, interpersonal skills, creative thinking, transdisciplinary thinking, and computational thinking.

Critical Work Functions: Their critical work functions include gathering and evaluating user requirements; designing UI architecture and strategy; conducting usability testing on UIs; optimizing UI designs; and managing people and the organization. This includes tasks like reviewing requirements for user interfaces (UIs) and providing advice on design aspects, evaluating overall user experience concept and design specifications to inform UI design, advising stakeholders on the feasibility of UI solutions and recommending alternatives, overseeing the preparation of UI design specifications, and advising on new and/or innovative UI concepts. They oversee UI design direction to ensure alignment with branding elements, standards, and guidelines, develop strategies for UI design and development to ensure business and user needs and requirements are met, advise on designing user interfaces for varied platforms or applications, provide technical inputs for transferring content and layout into an intuitive and responsive interface experience for users, explore and drive adopting new technologies or methodologies to design UIs, formulate organizational UI design guidelines, best practices and standards, synthesize findings and insights from research and feedback to develop design iterations, and establish a user testing lab for UIs' design and testing. Their work involves determining modifications in UI designs based on usability test findings and approving UI designs.

They develop UI design performance indicators, review frameworks and reporting standards, explore enhancing UI designs based on new and innovative technologies, oversee enhancements to UI designs based on user feedback and design audits, oversee quantitative analysis design and execution, and develop methods and procedures for process control, process improvement, sampling,

testing, inspection and training. They manage budget expenditure and allocation across teams and projects, monitor and track the team’s achievements and key performance indicators, propose new operational plans, including targeted budgets, work allocations and staff forecasts, acquire, allocate and optimize resources, develop learning roadmaps to support the team's professional development, and manage the performance and development process, including providing coaching and development opportunities to maximize each individual's potential.
